review_blob: Had this one on draught.  Nice apperance.  Deep rich color.  Aroma pleasant yet firm.  Aroma Full of maltiness and some hops.  Taste is full and satisfying.  Beer has an overall pleasant taste with a rich body and aftertaste.

This is decent European lager.  Apperance is nice when poured into a glass.  Nice, thick foam and very good lacing.  Aroma is OK, but gets pretty sulfury as it warms.  Taste is pretty decent and has a nice malty end.  Ive had this one in the green bottle and the 16 oz. can.  Gotta say, the green bottles are usually skunked.  Prefer this one out of a can.

OK everyone, this one is really quite good.  Lets face it, the hardest type of beer to make is a light lager.  Without big flavors, there is nowhere to hide brewing errors.  With BL, AB makes a clean light lager.  There is slight noble hop aroma when poured into a glass.  The taste is clean and balanced.

Maybe Im being too harsh of a judge based on what a value this brew.  To put this in context, we are talking about a good value for the cost.  My critisism is that the brewers came really close to making something outstanding like the Winterfest, but it didnt quite make it.  The apperance and freshness of this beer were great.  There were a couple issues with the aroma a drinkability.  The aroma was similar to the Bohemian lager aroma.  Maybe it is an excessive acetyladehyde I get from an incomplete fermentation or shortened aging time.  The taste lacks complexity and is somewhat coarse.  But again, something definately worth trying and worth the money.  Given the choice, I would purchase the Winterfest.

This brew was not nearly as good as the other Trader Joe flavors.  A definiate "green beer" aroma comes through if you pour this one in a glass.  Maybe aceyaldehyde or DMS ???  Kinda reminded me of a warm Coors Light aroma for some reason.  Taste is OK but raw hoppy and unbalanced.

Nice brew overall.  The aroma is that of a malty bock style beer.  The full flavor of the roasted and munich malts comes through on the taste.  Hints of coffee and light smokiness apparent on the aftertaste.  This is a powerfull brew and and exceptional value for the money.

This brew is rare example of "old world" quality.  The dark malt protects both the aroma and flavor from oxidation.  The aroma is that of soft, aromatic hops.  The most expensive type.  The taste is delicate and robust at the same time.  This is due to the malt, decotion mashing, soft water and long (by western standards) lager time.  An exceptional value and almost always "fresh" tasting.
